06768nam a22010335i 9780231544788DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018048961  a97802315447887 a10.7312/alle183182doi  a(DE-B1597)526864  a(OCoLC)1107989811  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHM480b.T73 2019 7aPHI0400002bisacsh04a150.19/522300aTransitional Subjects :bCritical Theory and Object Relations /ced. by Amy Allen, Brian O'Connor. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Directions in Critical Theory ;v6700tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tI. CONCEPTUAL FOUNDATIONS -- t1. Fusion or Omnipotence? A Dialogue -- t2. Hate, Aggression, and Recognition: Winnicott, Klein, and Honneth -- t3. Narcissism and Critique: On Kohut’s Self Psychology -- tII. HISTORICAL ENCOUNTERS -- t4. Progress and the Death Drive -- t5. Transitional Objects, God, and Modeling the Commodity Form -- t6 A “True-Enough Self ”: Winnicott, Object Relations Theory, and the Bases of Identity -- tIII. POLITICAL IMPLICATIONS -- t7. Intersubjectivity on the Couch: Recognition and Destruction in the Work of Jessica Benjamin -- t8. Politics and the Fear of Breakdown -- t9. Who Is the Perpetrator? The Missing Affect in Torture’s Violation of Human Dignity -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCritical social theory has long been marked by a deep, creative, and productive relationship with psychoanalysis. Whereas Freud and Fromm were important cornerstones for the early Frankfurt School, recent thinkers have drawn on the object-relations school of psychoanalysis. Transitional Subjects is the first book-length collection devoted to the engagement of critical theory with the work of Melanie Klein, Donald Winnicott, and other members of this school. Featuring contributions from some of the leading figures working in both of these fields, including Axel Honneth, Joel Whitebook, Noëlle McAfee, Sara Beardsworth, and C. Fred Alford, it provides a synoptic overview of current research at the intersection of these two theoretical traditions while also opening up space for further innovations.Transitional Subjects offers a range of perspectives on the critical potential of object-relations psychoanalysis, including feminist and Marxist views, to offer valuable insight into such fraught social issues as aggression, narcissism, “progress,” and torture. The productive dialogue that emerges augments our understanding of the self as intersubjectively and socially constituted and of contemporary “social pathologies.” Transitional Subjects shows how critical theory and object-relations psychoanalysis, considered together, have not only enriched critical theory but also invigorated psychoanalysis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aCritical theory. 0aObject relations (Psychoanalysis) 0aPsychoanalysis and philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Critical Theory.2bisacsh1 aAlessandro, Ferrara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlford, C. Fred.1 aAllen, Amy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAllen, Amy.1 aAmy, Allen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAxel, Honneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeardsworth, Sara.1 aBrian, O’Connor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aC. Fred, Alford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerrera, Alessandro.1 aHonneth, Axel.1 aHulatt, Owen.1 aJames, Martel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r